{"award_age":53.0,"bio_image":null,"category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1941-07-01T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":null,"gender":"male","image_urls":[],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Alfred_G._Gilman","mini_bio":"<p><b>Alfred Goodman Gilman<\/b> (born July 1, 1941) is an <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States\" title=\"United States\">American<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Pharmacology\" title=\"Pharmacology\">pharmacologist<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Biochemistry\" title=\"Biochemistry\">biochemist<\/a>. He shared the 1994 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a> with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Martin_Rodbell\" title=\"Martin Rodbell\">Martin Rodbell<\/a> for their discoveries regarding G-proteins.<\/p><p><b><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/G-protein\" title=\"G-protein\" class=\"mw-redirect\">G-proteins<\/a><\/b> are a vital intermediary between the extracellular activation of receptors (<b><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/G_protein-coupled_receptor\" title=\"G protein-coupled receptor\" class=\"mw-redirect\">GPCR<\/a><\/b>) on the cell membrane and actions within the cell. Rodbell had shown in the 1960s that <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Guanosine_triphosphate\" title=\"Guanosine triphosphate\">GTP<\/a> was involved in cell signaling. It was Gilman who actually discovered the proteins that interacted with the GTP to initiate <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Signal_transduction\" title=\"Signal transduction\">signalling cascades<\/a> within the cell.<\/p>","name":"Alfred G. Gilman","place_of_birth":"New Haven, Connecticut","place_of_death":null,"text":"Alfred G. Gilman , Physiology or Medicine, 1994","year":1994.0}